---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="World Cup Predictor Case Study | Ross Lyall Portfolio"
  description="Case study for World Cup Predictor, a private 2026 World Cup group-stage prediction app."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <main>
      <section class="case-hero case-hero--predictor">
        <a class="back-link" href="/">← Back to portfolio</a>

        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study / Home App / Private Tool</p>
        <h1>World Cup Predictor</h1>
        <p class="case-hero__lead">
          A private World Cup 2026 group-stage simulator for entering
          predictions and actual scores, recalculating live tables and using the
          app from a phone during the tournament.
        </p>

        <div class="case-meta">
          <span>React</span>
          <span>Vite</span>
          <span>Express</span>
          <span>SQLite</span>
          <span>PWA</span>
          <span>Tailscale</span>
          <span>Private football prediction app</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Screenshots</p>
          <h2>
            Private app, built to work properly on a phone during the tournament
          </h2>
          <p>
            These screenshots show the private app in use: group tables,
            third-place rankings, fixtures and the installed Android PWA view.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="app-gallery app-gallery--trolley">
          <button
            class="app-gallery__item"
            type="button"
            data-lightbox-src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-groups-mobile.png"
            data-lightbox-alt="World Cup Predictor group tables mobile screenshot"
          >
            <img
              src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-groups-mobile.png"
              alt="World Cup Predictor group tables mobile screenshot"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <span>Installed App</span>
          </button>

          <button
            class="app-gallery__item"
            type="button"
            data-lightbox-src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-third-place-mobile.png"
            data-lightbox-alt="World Cup Predictor best third-place teams mobile screenshot"
          >
            <img
              src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-third-place-mobile.png"
              alt="World Cup Predictor best third-place teams mobile screenshot"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <span>Group Tables</span>
          </button>

          <button
            class="app-gallery__item"
            type="button"
            data-lightbox-src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-fixtures-mobile.png"
            data-lightbox-alt="World Cup Predictor fixtures mobile screenshot"
          >
            <img
              src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-fixtures-mobile.png"
              alt="World Cup Predictor fixtures mobile screenshot"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <span>All Fixtures</span>
          </button>

          <button
            class="app-gallery__item"
            type="button"
            data-lightbox-src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-installed-app.png"
            data-lightbox-alt="World Cup Predictor installed Android app screenshot"
          >
            <img
              src="/images/projects/world-cup-predictor/world-cup-predictor-installed-app.png"
              alt="World Cup Predictor installed Android app screenshot"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <span>Third-Place Teams</span>
          </button>
        </div>

        <p class="project-type">Private Tailscale app</p>

        <dialog class="image-lightbox" id="world-cup-predictor-lightbox">
          <button
            class="image-lightbox__close"
            type="button"
            aria-label="Close image"
          >
            ×
          </button>
          <img src="" alt="" />
        </dialog>

        <script>
          const lightbox = document.querySelector(
            "#world-cup-predictor-lightbox",
          ) as HTMLDialogElement | null;

          const lightboxImage = lightbox?.querySelector(
            "img",
          ) as HTMLImageElement | null;

          const closeButton = lightbox?.querySelector(
            ".image-lightbox__close",
          ) as HTMLButtonElement | null;

          const triggers = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>(
            "[data-lightbox-src]",
          );

          triggers.forEach((trigger) => {
            trigger.addEventListener("click", () => {
              const src = trigger.dataset.lightboxSrc;
              const alt = trigger.dataset.lightboxAlt || "";

              if (!lightbox || !lightboxImage || !src) return;

              lightboxImage.src = src;
              lightboxImage.alt = alt;
              lightbox.showModal();
            });
          });

          closeButton?.addEventListener("click", () => {
            lightbox?.close();
          });

          lightbox?.addEventListener("click", (event) => {
            if (event.target === lightbox) {
              lightbox.close();
            }
          });
        </script>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
          <h2>
            Following a World Cup group stage properly means keeping track of a
            lot more than individual scores.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            This project was built around a real use case: following the 2026
            World Cup group stage, entering score predictions, then comparing
            them with actual results as the tournament progresses.
          </p>

          <p>
            A simple notes app or spreadsheet can hold scores, but it does not
            quickly recalculate standings across all 12 groups or keep track of
            the best third-placed teams in a way that works well on a phone.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The solution</p>
          <h2>
            A private simulator that handles predictions, actual results and
            tournament table logic in one place.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            World Cup Predictor supports all 12 World Cup groups, lets scores be
            entered for each match, calculates standings from those scores and
            tracks the best third-placed teams as the picture changes.
          </p>

          <p>
            It was kept private on purpose. Rather than pushing a short-term
            personal project into a public hosted stack, it runs from an
            always-on PC using a local Express and SQLite backend, with
            Tailscale providing secure access from a phone.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Key features</p>
          <h2>What World Cup Predictor does</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>All 12 groups</h3>
            <p>
              Covers the full 2026 World Cup group stage rather than a small
              sample dataset or partial simulator.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Score entry</h3>
            <p>
              Lets predicted and actual scores be entered match by match, making
              it easy to move between forecast and reality.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Live standings</h3>
            <p>
              Recalculates group tables from entered scores so positions, goal
              difference and points update immediately.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Third-place ranking</h3>
            <p>
              Tracks the best third-placed teams, which is one of the more
              awkward parts to monitor manually.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>Match statuses</h3>
            <p>
              Supports Prediction, Actual and Final result states so the app
              stays useful before, during and after matchdays.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>06</span>
            <h3>Phone-first use</h3>
            <p>
              Refined for mobile use, backed up with localStorage and installed
              on Android as a PWA for quick access during the tournament.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Architecture</p>
          <h2>Built to stay simple, private and easy to run</h2>
          <p>
            The technical choices were driven by the project being useful for a
            single household tournament workflow rather than needing a public
            SaaS setup.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="flow-grid">
          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>React + Vite</h3>
            <p>
              The front end handles the score entry screens, group views and
              mobile-first app layout.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Express server</h3>
            <p>
              A local Express app provides a simple backend for storing and
              updating scores and match states.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>SQLite</h3>
            <p>
              SQLite keeps the data layer lightweight and practical for a
              short-term private project.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Always-on PC</h3>
            <p>
              The app runs from a home PC that stays available during the
              tournament rather than relying on external hosting.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>Tailscale + PWA</h3>
            <p>
              Tailscale Serve provides private HTTPS access, which makes the app
              installable on Android and usable away from home.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Design thinking</p>
          <h2>
            The app was shaped by real matchday use rather than by trying to
            look like a public football product.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            Mobile use mattered early because this is the sort of tool that gets
            checked on a sofa, in the garden or while watching a match, not only
            at a desk. That pushed the layout towards faster taps, clearer
            states and easier scrolling between groups.
          </p>

          <p>
            localStorage backup was added as a practical safety net, and the
            backend stayed deliberately small because Supabase or a more public
            deployment would have been unnecessary overhead for this project.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">What I learned</p>
          <h2>Useful lessons from building it</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="lesson-list">
          <article>
            <h3>Private infrastructure can be the right answer</h3>
            <p>
              For a short-term personal tool, a local Express and SQLite setup
              was quicker and more sensible than forcing in a heavier hosted
              stack.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Tournament logic needs careful edge-case thinking</h3>
            <p>
              Recalculating standings is straightforward in principle, but
              keeping table and third-place logic reliable across many groups
              takes care.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Phone use changes what matters</h3>
            <p>
              The most useful improvements were not visual extras but better tap
              targets, clearer status handling and a smoother installed-app
              experience.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-next">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Future improvements</p>
          <h2>Where World Cup Predictor could go next</h2>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li>
            Add knockout-stage prediction handling after group qualification is
            settled.
          </li>
          <li>
            Refine tie-break explanations so table movements are easier to
            follow.
          </li>
          <li>
            Improve backup and restore flows beyond the current localStorage
            safety net.
          </li>
          <li>
            Add a clearer comparison view between predicted and actual outcomes.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
